{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_foster_ver01/data/sn85038485/00513684095/1923101801/0377.xml":{"full_text":"FREIGHT HE CUT\nSEEN IS SOLUTION\nOF FARM PROBLEM\nIowa Congressman Declares\nDifference Of Few Cents\nMight Mean Much\nEditor's Note: President Coolidge is\ndiscussing with railroad executives the\nnecessity of cutting freight rates on farm\nproducts to relieve the depressing market\nsituation. Some have objected that the\npossible reductions would be too small to\naffect prices. Representative L. .T. Dick\ninson of Iowa, a member of the house\nf\u00bbvm bloc, is back from four months in\nthe wheat belt. In the following exclu\nsive article he discussed this remedy\nfrom a new angle.\nBy Ti. J. DICKINSON\n(By I.eaNed Wire to The Age-Herald.)\nWASHINGTON, Oct. 17.\u2014After a\ncareful survey of agricultural con\nditions nr the middle west it is very\napparent that the farmer is not able\nto cope economically with the other\ncontending factors that make up the\neconomic equation of the present\nday.\nThe condition of the farmer cannot\nall be credited to inflated land\nvalues, or the improvement of his\nbuildings on Tiis farm or to the pur*\nchase of new automobiles or farm\nmachinery.\nThe manufacturer is able to pro\ntect himself, either by holding his\nproduct off the market or by curtail\ning the production thereof, and\nthereby bridge himself over a busi\nness depression. Labor has also\nfound a way by organization, where\nin it can protect itself from depres\nsion in wages, and both labor and\nindustry have been able to maintain\na higher price level for their prod\nucts than the unorganized farmer.\nFor this reason, the deflation fol\nlowing the Avar has not materially\naffected many industries; has not re\nduced materially the price of labor,\nbut has materially deflated the\nearning power of the farmer. He\nmust sell his produce at the deflated\nprice and buy his merchandise at the\ninflated price. This is the real cause\nof the business depression in the\n'middle west.\nMany theories have been given to\nshow that the farmer is back on the\npre-war basis of the year 1913, but\nitheSe theories do not take into con\nsideration all of the elements with\nwhich the farmer has to contend.\nMost writers dwell entirely on the\niprice level of farm products and do\n!not take into the account the pur\nchasing power of his dollar.\nMany discussions are also heard\nwith reference to the cost of mar\nketing farm products, particularly\nInvolving freight. I.ong articles have\n[been written showing that the dif\nference in freight per bushel is only\n2 or 3 cents on various items.\nNo attempt is made by these au\nthors to show how the difference of\n12 or 3 'cents per bushel in the trans\nportation charges may limit or cur\ntail the marketing of the farmer's\niproduct in certain areas, in compe\ntttlch with other producers of the\n'same article.\nA reduction of the freight charges\nof a few cents per bushel might\nopen up a new area, wherein the\nfarmer could market his product in\ncompetition with foreign products.\niand no one can foretell just how far\na. few cents per bushel in transpor\ntation would affect the market price\nof any given commodity.\n(Copyright, 1923.)\nI\nRealty Transfers\nNannie H. Anderson to J. B. Royal,\n,parts of Lots 1 and 2 in *Block 642, ac\n!cording: to survey by Elyton Land cora\ncording\nIpany, for $6,260.\nClyde Hardy Nelson to Margaret H.\nilrish, part of Lot B in Block 10, accord\ning to Birmingham Realty company\u2019s sec\nfond addition to Forest Park, for $3,000\nand assumption of mortgage for $7,600.\nGeorge A. Millar to Fred Bouchet and\n,Leoni Bouchet, Lots 61 and 62 as shown\n,in plat and survey of Tuskegee Place in j\nprobate office, for $3,150.\nC. C. Snider and wife to C. C. Snider\nCigar and Tobacco company, 80 feet in\nLots 1 and 2. subdivision B. according to\nsurvey by Elyton Land company, for\n$5,000 and assumption of mortgage.\nA. L. Dillon and wife to A. H. Fore,\nLot 11 and part of Lot 12 in Block 1, ac\ncording to High Cliff Land, company\u2019s\nsurvey, for $2,500.\nWilliam R. Thrasher to A. L. Dillon\nand Mamie R. Dillon. Lots 11, 12 and 13\nin Block 23. according to map of Rugby\n3.and and improvement company, for\n$5 000.\nBirmingham Trust and Savings com\nSanv to Dorothy B. Jacobson, Lot 2 in\nlook 225. according to survey of Elyton\n3.and company, for $4,000.\nNorris Burgess to S. A. Cruce. Lot 6 in\nBlock 16, according to map of East Lake\nLand company, for $5,100.\nNAMED FOR HARDING\nAVON PARK. Fla., Oct. 17.\u2014The\nnew quarter million dollar bridge,\nspanning the Kissimee river on the\nmain highway between Tampa and\nMiami, has been named the Warren\nHarding memorial bridge. It also\nwas decided to establish a Warren\nHarding memorial park of 40 acres\n\u00a3>n each side of the bridge to be pre\nsented to Congress as a national\n[park.\nGLEASON QUITS SOX\nCHICAGO, Oct. 16.\u2014William \u201cKid\u201d\npleason, manager of the White Sox,\niChicago American league team, who\ntoday presented Charles Comisky with\na series title, 'Will tomorrow present\nthe White Sox owner with his resig\naation. according to the Chicago\nTribune.\nFacts about\nChild-birth\nN eminent physician has\nshown to thousands of ex\npectant mothers just how to be\nfree from dread, and from much of\nthe suffering which many mothers\nexperience for months, right up to\nthe moment when tho Little One\narrives!\nMrs. Wm. Washington, 107\nLouise Ave., Nashville, Tenn.,\ntays: \u201cThere is positively no wo\nman on earth that would he with\nout \u2018Mother\u2019s Friend\u2019 during ex\npectancy if she only knew the\nvalue o\u00a3 comfort.\u201d\n\u201cMother\u2019s Friend\u201d is externally\napplied to the region of the abdo\nmen, back and hips. It relieves the\ntension on nerves and ligaments\nas month follows month. Finally,\nit makes child-birth a joy instead\nof a painful dread.\nUse \u201cMother\u2019s Friend\u201d as our\nmothers and grandmothers did.\nDon\u2019t wait, start today, and mean\nwhile write to Bradfleld Regulator\nCo., BA-72, Atlanta, Ga., foi free\nwonderful book containing infor\nmation every expectant mother\nshould have. Get a bottle of\n\u201cMother\u2019s Friend\u201d today. It is\n\u25a0old by all good druggists.\nA Selling of 1,372 New Fall Frocks In An\nEvent That Will Long Be Remembered\nThat Were Made to Sell at $5Q and $60\nOnly after many weeks\u2019 preparation and unusual concessions from manufacturers are we able to offer such\na wonderful array of values, such as we have gathered for this, the most spectacular dress sale in the history\nof the Pizitz store.\nThese are the frocks that follow closely the lines of much more expensive models\u2014embodying the very\nlatest fashion hints and are made of the season\u2019s most popular silks and woolens, exquisite creations that\ngive expression to every authoritative phase of the dress mode for fall and winter.\nThis is a sale beyond compare\u2014when you see these beautiful dresses today\u2014compare the styles and the\nvalues with what you might expect for the price, you are going to agree that never in your life have you ever\nseen an event of such magnitude or one that affords such astonishing savings.\nThe Colors:\nThe Trimmings:\nMarvelous Embroidery\nBeautiful Beading\nButtons\nBraiding\nVelvet Trimming\nBell Sleeves\nOrgandy Collar and Cuffs\nEvery wanted color for fall and\nwinter wear. You must see this re\nmarkable display and sale.\nThe Styles and Materials:\nShimmering Satin\nChiffon Velvet\nFinest Poirets\nCanton Crepes\nSatin Crepe\nFlat Crepe\nGeorgette\nGorgeous Evening Gowns\nDinner Gowns\nStreet Dresses\nBusiness Frocks\nTo be sure, there are over 1,000 dresses and plenty for selection, but we can\nnot guarantee this. So would advise you to come early while choosing is at its\nbest.\nFinal Preparations Have Been Made\nTo Make This Our Greatest\nThe\nMaterials:\nOrmondales\nTriconettes\nSilk-Finished Bolivias\nVelona\nRoi de Laine\n\nAnd many other popular\nmaterials for fall and winter\nwear,\nThe \"t**'1*~\nTrimmings:\nTrimmed with beauti\nful, luxurious fur collar\nand cuffs, while others\nare strictly tailored. Sil\nhouettes, side drapes,\nstraight lines and ripple\nsides. Made to sell at\n59.50 to $75.\nDistinctive Styles and Unusual Values Are the Outstanding Features\nLuxurious coats in rich luxurious types, lavishly trimmed in selected furs\u2014a sale that will demonstrate .the possibilities of coat values, ^^e are of\nfering today values that will prove that Pizitz coats stand prominent and distinctive in Birmingham. The luxurious collars of rich furs, and the elegant\nlinings establish them as extraordinary in quality and the styles are always the smartest of the season. You can quickly see that elusive spirit of individual\nity which so exclusively characterizes Pizitz apparel, is instantly visible in these coats\u2014to be one of those who get the better selection.\nPOSITIVELY beyond belief. Simply wonderful coat values\nthat we offer BELOW wholesale cost. This sale is another\nmilestone along the marvelous Road of Savings which invariably\nleads to Pizitz. Our buyers have frequently done wonderful\nthings, but this event positively takes first place. BE ON HAND\nWHEN THE DOORS OPEN.\n(THIRD FLOOR\u2014NEW BUILDING)\nEVERY solitary coat is an exceptional value. They repre\nsent weeks of patient search, weeks of planning and ne\ngotiating, but the results justifies the effort, for the patrons of this\nstore will find the greatest, grandest fur-trimmed coats awaiting\nthem that perseverance, determination and years of experience\ncan discover.\n(THIRD FLOOR\u2014NEW BUILDING)","height":"27672","width":"21696"}}
